Borut Petrič (born 28 December 1961 in <a href="/wiki/Kranj" title="Kranj">Kranj</a>, <a href="/wiki/Slovenia" title="Slovenia">Slovenia</a>) is a former Slovenian <a href="/wiki/Freestyle_swimming" title="Freestyle swimming">freestyle</a> <a href="/wiki/Swimmer" title="Swimmer" class="mw-redirect">swimmer</a>, who represented <a href="/wiki/Yugoslavia" title="Yugoslavia">Yugoslavia</a> in three consecutive <a href="/wiki/Summer_Olympics" title="Summer Olympics" class="mw-redirect">Summer Olympics</a>, starting in 1976. A brother of swimmer <a href="/wiki/Darjan_Petri%C4%8D" title="Darjan Petrič">Darjan Petrič</a>, he won the silver medal in the men's 1500&#160; m freestyle at the <a href="/wiki/1978_World_Aquatics_Championships" title="1978 World Aquatics Championships">1978 World Aquatics Championships</a> in <a href="/wiki/Berlin" title="Berlin">Berlin</a>. Petrič was the youngest participant (14 years, 325 days) at the <a href="/wiki/1976_Summer_Olympics" title="1976 Summer Olympics">1976 Summer Olympics</a> in <a href="/wiki/Montreal, _Canada" title="Montreal, Canada" class="mw-redirect">Montreal, Canada</a>. He also won a gold medal on 400&#160; m freestyle in 1981. In the same year, Petrič received the award for best athlete of <a href="/wiki/Socialist_Federal_Republic_of_Yugoslavia" title="Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia">Yugoslavia</a>. He is the coach at swimming club Fužinar Ravne.
.
